Between lettuce which are half way through the cropping season, with another five weeks still of harvest to come from them, I am sowing carrots for autumn. This is fourth of June and it’s a great time over the next two weeks to sow  wherever you can find space. By mid July the lettuce will finish and I twist them out, and the carrots then fill all the space quite quickly. This is no dig and easy and quick.

node.text:
I’ll show you a bed here where we just finished harvesting parsnips, and the soil has received no food for 15 months, we are about to spread some compost on it.

Next to it is where we harvested carrots in December and then spread 2.5 cm/1 inch compost and I show you how beautiful and soft it is now. Also how to rake it to prepare for sowing.

node.title: Bed prep no dig with soil before and after mulching, then a light rake

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 11, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: We’ve had good rain and the greens are green! Brussels sprouts are promising for October onwards, kale is yielding loads and carrots sown 4th June (under mesh against root fly) are almost ready - all second plantings after carrot, lettuce and spinach. My new book appearing January is Skills for Successful Growing and we got some lovely photos for it this morning with the incredible @jasoningram

node.text: Two fine helpers for a few days @adam_bowers_uk and @ateenandhistrowel, both growing no dig at home already. Adam is tipping shredded hedge prunings to compost and Jamie is edging with long handled shears

node.text: Evening tour of Homeacres no dig garden with the beehives top left at the beginning

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 07, 2021. May be an image of nature and body of water.

node.text: I love the underestimated beauty in vegetable gardens! Even with the white covers which in this case are protecting carrots from root fly, and salads from rabbits. My favourite flowers now are the summer zinnias, sown undercover in April with marigolds as well, sunflowers sown early May undercover and dahlias which survive winter here as bulbs in the ground, from @sarahravensgarden originally as seed. #nodig helps because we build the beauty instead of needing to weed, see my no dig online course and book on website. Today is a day course here and I hope the sunshine continues, but think it may not!!

node.text: It’s a delight to walk in the greenhouse and meet the aroma of ripe melon, all four of these Alvaro are ready at the same time (see post of one week ago), and that’s an early harvest in our climate. Swipe to see the flesh, also two Emir melons I cut this morning. The four Alvaro weigh 3.2kg, taste amazing.

node.text: We removed the mesh cover today to put it over carrots against fly. These Brussels were interplanted mid June between carrots, as succession second crop and no compost added for them, or feeds. Simple easy no dig. Learn more in my online Brussels lesson of course 3 available on my website

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 02, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text: I found two pieces of old corrugated iron which fit neatly over two of the three compost heaps. The middle heap has finished compost which has been turned from the heap nearest to camera. The far heap is full. The maturing plus finished compost heaps are best without rain going in too much. We just had 29 mm / over an inch of rain in one hour and that makes compost soggy, less sweet. But it’s less harmful to a heap being filled regularly, like the nearest one here. Heaps have soil under - the card is only to suppress weeds around edges. Watch out for a video on my You Tube channel about all this, in late August. Before that will be a video about no dig potatoes.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on August 01, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text: We have been lacking blue sky so this is a special evening. Homeacres is looking lush, the zinnias are gorgeous, and you can join me on a tour of the garden, on my latest video which we just posted to YouTube, filmed three days ago

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on July 31, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: Lush green after the rain, includes wild rocket, new planting of chicory under mesh, new planting of leeks in the middle, brussels sprouts under mesh further up and asparagus growing tall. No Dig means the weeding is not onerous and we can keep up with all the succession plantings. Much of the garden has new plants since June, at the same time as harvesting lots of vegetables

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Charles Dowding on July 29, 2021. May be an image of fruit and outdoors.

node.text: Growth in the greenhouse has been fast and these are Alvaro melons, plug plants from @delflandorganic, and Sakura tomatoes I sowed mid-March. Soil mulched with 2.5cm / one inch compost in May. There s a little red spider mite on melon leaves and I hope they ripen while leaves are still green.
